  "prompt": "Which is the best book for maths?",
  "response": "The \"best\" math book can vary depending on your level of expertise, interests, and goals. Here are some highly regarded books across various areas of mathematics:\n\n1. **For Beginners:**\n   - *\"The Joy of x: A Guided Tour of Math, from One to Infinity\"* by Steven Strogatz \u2013 This book provides an accessible introduction to various mathematical concepts in a relatable manner.\n\n2. **For High School Students:**\n   - *\"Algebra\"* by Israel M. Gelfand and Alexander Shen \u2013 A classic that emphasizes understanding algebraic concepts deeply.\n\n3. **For College Students:**\n   - *\"Calculus\"* by Michael Spivak \u2013 A rigorous introduction to calculus, ideal for those who want a deep understanding of the subject.\n   - *\"Linear Algebra Done Right\"* by Sheldon Axler \u2013 A clear and comprehensive guide to linear algebra, focusing on vector spaces and linear transformations.\n\n4. **For Advanced Students:**\n   - *\"Principles of Mathematical Analysis\"* by Walter Rudin \u2013 Often referred to as \"Baby Rudin,\" this book is a standard text for introductory real analysis.\n   - *\"Algebra\"* by Serge Lang \u2013 A comprehensive and rigorous treatment of algebra.\n\n5. **For Problem Solving:**\n   - *\"The Art and Craft of Problem Solving\"* by Paul Zeitz \u2013 This book not only teaches problem-solving techniques but also encourages creative thinking in mathematics.\n\n6. **For a Broad Overview:**\n   - *\"Mathematics: A Very Short Introduction\"* by Timothy Gowers \u2013 A concise overview of mathematics and its significance in various fields.\n\nChoose a book that matches your current level and interests, and you'll likely find it to be the best fit for you!",
